attitude and expectation are more common than divergent or unique experiences. The key revelation of the work is that, despite a number of peculiarities characterising their individual and collective experiences of migration, both the Irish and Scots were relatively successful migrants in the period under consideration. Using interviews, both spoken and written, and tackling issues of why and how versions of the past are represented and what they mean, this fascinating study considers individual and collective memory and the use of personal testimonies as historical evidence: their uniqueness and typicality. Furthermore, in using personal narratives the book portrays individual migration experiences which are often hidden in studies based on statistical analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aGroup identity. 0aIrishxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aScotsxSocial life and customsy20th century. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aAustralasia.  aAustralia.  aCanada.  aEllis Island Museum.  aIrish migrants.  aNew Zealand.  aNorth America.  aScottish migrants.  acollective experiences.  acollective memory.  adiasporic approaches.  aemigration.  aethnic identities.  aindividual memory.  amigrant encounters.  amigrant groups.  anational identities.  ashared experiences.  atransnational approaches.1 aMcCarthy, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129895/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUP